Beyond the listed 15 categories, several additional threats are becoming more relevant in 2026:

1. Identity Infrastructure Attacks

Attackers increasingly compromise identity providers (IdPs), leading to cascading access across entire enterprise ecosystems. Once an IdP is breached, traditional perimeter controls become largely ineffective and thus should be monitored very closely to avoid supply chain attacks.

2. API Exploitation
Modern applications rely heavily on APIs, and attackers are now targeting:
0) Broken authentication in APIs
1) Excessive data exposure
2) Lack of rate limiting
3) This expands OWASP API Security risks significantly beyond traditional web application threats.
3. Quantum-Adjacent Cryptographic Risk
Although full quantum computing threats are still emerging, “harvest now, decrypt later” strategies are already active. Encrypted data is being stolen today with the expectation it will be decrypted in the future.

4. Autonomous Malware Systems
Malware is increasingly capable of:
0) Self-modifying behavior
1) Environment-aware execution
2) Avoiding sandbox detection dynamically

